The magnitude of the cross product of two vectors \( \vec{B} \) and \( \vec{C} \) can be found using the formula:

\[ |\vec{C} \times \vec{B}| = |\vec{C}| \cdot |\vec{B}| \cdot \sin(\theta) \]

where \( \theta \) is the angle between the two vectors. However, without the angle, we can find the cross product directly using the components of the vectors and then calculate its magnitude.

Given:
\[ \vec{B} = -2\hat{i} - 6\hat{j} + 2\hat{k} \]
\[ \vec{C} = -5\hat{i} - 2\hat{j} - 3\hat{k} \]

The cross product \( \vec{C} \times \vec{B} \) is calculated using the determinant of a matrix with the unit vectors \( \hat{i}, \hat{j}, \hat{k} \) in the first row, the components of \( \vec{C} \) in the second row, and the components of \( \vec{B} \) in the third row:

\[ 
\vec{C} \times \vec{B} = 
\begin{vmatrix}
\hat{i} & \hat{j} & \hat{k} \\
-5 & -2 & -3 \\
-2 & -6 & 2 \\
\end{vmatrix}
\]

To compute the cross product, we have:

\[ \vec{C} \times \vec{B} =
\begin{vmatrix}
-2 & -3 \\
-6 & 2 \\
\end{vmatrix}
\hat{i}
- \begin{vmatrix}
-5 & -3 \\
-2 & 2 \\
\end{vmatrix}
\hat{j} + \begin{vmatrix}
-5 & -2 \\
-2 & -6 \\
\end{vmatrix}
\hat{k} \]

Calculating each determinant:

\[ \vec{C} \times \vec{B} =
((-2) \cdot 2 - (-3) \cdot (-6))\hat{i}
- ((-5) \cdot 2 - (-3) \cdot (-2))\hat{j}
+ ((-5) \cdot (-6) - (-2) \cdot (-2))\hat{k} \]

\[ \vec{C} \times \vec{B} =
(-4 - 18)\hat{i}
- (-10 - 6)\hat{j}
+ (30 - 4)\hat{k} \]

\[ \vec{C} \times \vec{B} =
(-22)\hat{i}
+ (16)\hat{j}
+ (26)\hat{k} \]

\[ \vec{C} \times \vec{B} =
 -22\hat{i}
+ 16\hat{j}
+ 26\hat{k} \]

Now, we calculate the magnitude of \( \vec{C} \times \vec{B} \):

\[ |\vec{C} \times \vec{B}| = \sqrt{(-22)^2 + (16)^2 + (26)^2} \]

\[ |\vec{C} \times \vec{B}| = \sqrt{484 + 256 + 676} \]

\[ |\vec{C} \times \vec{B}| = \sqrt{1416} \]

\[ |\vec{C} \times \vec{B}| = 37.6 \]

Thus, the magnitude of \( \vec{C} \times \vec{B} \) is closest to 37.6.
